origReviewText: You are looking at one of Kodak's finer digital cameras.. Because this was the beginning of the "mp" where more was not necessarily better.. I recall the craze when everyone kept demanding higher mp! I personally wouldnt trade my 2mp camera for the big 10mp anyday!. This camera, if you can find one as no one who has one is willing to part with it as it still to this day takes crisper cleaner better focused pictures than the digital cameras today.. MY RECOMMENDATION:BEST DIGITAL PRO CAMERAS OUT THERE!. MY RATING: AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA++++++. **be sure to check all my 100% honest accurate reviews!**

I had just purchased my  third Olympus one D340 R and two D360L the pace I put these cameras through , surprised me how long they lasted. the only trouble I had with the other too is a flimsily battery door latch, both finally gave way and I had to make my own door latch ;. I am reading  reviews on here and all state there is no zoom. the camera has one zoom on it, you hit the + and you get a zoom in on your subject. hit - and it moves to a farther out view. but with my Kodak reader I can transfer my pictures to my PC, and make them as big as I like. then I put them on DVD to make a slide show. for the money you can't beat the camera, just wish Olympus would beef up there battery door latch. The D360R I have now still works but had to make  my own latch to hold the batteries in. over all I would give it 4 and a half stars, better latch for the battery door would be a 5 star.

I have owned this camera for over 7 years now and it has never let me down. Back in 2007, you didn't have a lot of options for hybrid camera/video recorder. There were a couple, but the megapixels were low or it had slow shutter speed. I was very lucky though, at CES in 2006 Canon came out with the TX1.. Here is the killer features folks, Optical Zoom and 720P. This baby has 10x Optical Zoom. Which was huge back then for a hybrid. In addition it has 7.1MP and records in 720P. The lens tucks itself back in and has a little shutter and its all automatic. Even has a standby power program in case you left it running. Software wise it works very well, easy to navigate the LCD. Finally, when your all done it can fit in your pocket. The camera is a little larger than a pack of cigarettes or playing cards, whichever you prefer.. The only drawback to all that glory is storage. At the time I had to keep a laptop nearby to offload video and pictures each day. Even though I was using two 8GB SDHC cards. When recording video, it literally ate through 1GB or so every 15 min.. Flash forward to 2014 and my TX1 has gone to many places. Multiple States, Australia, and recently South Africa on Safari.

If you've read anything about the Leica M8 on the internet you've undoubtedly heard about all of its "issues," so I won't bother going over them to any great extent, but I will add my thoughts on them.. The shutter is louder than a film Leica, no doubt about it, but it's not really loud either.  I'd agree with what some people have said about the shutter making a different kind of noise, but honestly it's as loud as pretty much any DSLR these days.  Of course, there are a couple of advantages to the noisier shutter in the M8 versus the quieter one in the M9, M8.2 and so-called M8.1, such as 1/8000th second top shutter speed and 1/250th flash sync.  In a professional-grade camera, I really appreciate the higher flash sync, so I'll put up with a slightly noisier--but not really noisy--shutter.. One thing that really bothers me:  why no PC-sync port?!  I know a lot of people say, "oh, well a M-rangefinder is about natural light shooting," but that's stupid.  Photography is about controlling light, whether it's existing or not, and sometimes I'd like to be able to plug some studio lights into the camera and still be able to use the shoe for additional viewfinders.  I can't believe the M9 still doesn't have a PC-sync port.. The camera itself is really rather unobtrusive--it's smallish and it looks like something you dug out of your grandpa's closet--unless someone happens to recognize it as a Leica.  It's sort of funny to watch people process why an "antique" camera like this has an LCD on the back, and inevitably they ask, "Is this digital?"  I've always wondered what they'd think if I said no.. I sort of have mixed feelings about removing the bottom plate to change the battery and the SD card, but it's not too much trouble; I know some people think it's a bother, but it is what it is.  Battery life is as you've heard: on the low side.  I usually take my M8 on vacation with me and I'm always careful to charge the battery every night; I'd like to just carry an extra battery pack, but they're stupidly pricey.  I'd guess about 400 shots to a charge when you're not doing a lot of image review.. It has a 1.33x crop factor compared to 35mm film, and that's a little annoying, but to me since it's a rangefinder and you're not actually looking through the lens it seems easier to me to adjust to than the 1.5x or 1.6x common to most DSLRs.  I would still appreciate a full frame sensor, but the M9, ME, and M Typ-240 are just more than I can honestly justify spending on a camera (and sometimes the M8 is as well).  I sold my Voigtlander Color-Skopar 35mm f/2.5 PII and replaced it with their Nokton Classic 35mm f/1.4 MC, and I'm fairly happy with it as a basic "normal" lens, and it wasn't too outrageously expensive.. The general conclusion on the internet is that the M8 is too noisy regarding higher ISO settings.  And I'd maybe agree, but while it's no D810 or 5D Mark III, it's also an improvement over many APS-C DSLRs out there.  Noise aside, I've worked with files from a lot of different cameras and the M8 files have a crispness that I haven't been able to find in other cameras, and I'd wager that the lack of any anti-alias filter in the camera is the reason.  I've compared the M8 against the Canon 7D, and I'd conclude that, in terms of resolution, the M8 is a match for the 7D.  A camera like the 5D Mark III has an advantage at large print sizes, but I think up to 11x14 or so the M8 is a strong contender.. IR/UV sensitivity is an issue, and the whole black-into-magenta thing shows up pretty easily.  Leica sent me two filters to block it, but even with coded lenses the whole cyan corner shift is still a bit of an issue at times.  I've coded my lenses with markers, but my Zeiss and Leica lenses rub off too easily.  Voigtlander lenses have a nice groove in the mount to prevent the self-coding from wearing off, but I tend to favor Zeiss lenses, and I find myself recoding them every four or five lens changes.  But having an infrared sensitive camera is actually pretty nice, and a simple Hoya R72 visible light blocking filter is all that's needed to take advantage of it.  The best thing is that unlike on an SLR, focusing (and metering even!) is as easy as ever.. I actually sold off nearly all of my Canon kit in order to purchase more M-mount lenses.  I thought I'd keep the Canon stuff for the things that a rangefinder isn't suitable for, but it turned out that for what I was shooting a rangefinder could do 90% of it.  One thing that turned out to be pretty neat was that when I put my Canon ST-E2 wireless controller on my M8, I found out that if I used the 580EX II Speedlights set in manual wireless mode I could fire them off with a maximum sync-speed of 1/90th second!  I just had to make sure that the M8 wasn't set to second curtain sync or it'd miss the flash, but I was surprised that this worked at all.  In the end though, the 580s were sold and I've picked up some Nikon SB-24s and SB-28s that work great with the M8.. Anyway,  I really like the M8, but it's not a camera for everyone, and there's times that I really miss having a DSLR.  Having such an anachronistic camera is always going to be a bit of a struggle unless you're either wealthy enough to not really care about it, or have a specific enough shooting style that you can make the most of it.  I wouldn't really say that I'm either of those things, but every now and then everything comes together correctly and the M8 is the greatest camera I've ever used.

I have had this camera for what, 7 years now? Actually this is my second one. Let's just say this camera is definitely not waterproof.. I have taken this camera to numerous events and trips. I would say its a pretty reliable camera, I've gotten some really awesome photos from it. I would recommend this camera to someone who wants a good, easy-to-use camera. Be aware however, that this camera has major strengths and weaknesses (continued below):. Strengths: macro (close up photography), vivid colors, flowers, daylight, outdoors. Weaknesses: any low-light situations (indoors and outdoors), dull colors (settings can be adjusted for cloudy days- this is a must if you get this camera, it will make your photos look so rich and amazing), high contrast (taking a photo against a bright window for example. this is universal problem for most cameras). So if you plan on getting some heavy use out of this camera in any time before sunrise or after sunset, be ready to be deeply disappointed. I've tried tripods, the self-timer setting, the twilight settings.  nothing works! They all come out horribly. Fuzzy, unflattering. just ugh.. Other than that. this camera is not too shabby. I have gotten some spectacular photos from it even though it is just a digital camera. It's a good size too, feels good in the hand, makes it easy to take steady shots. The shutter button is much better than the ones on most standard digital cameras, yet nowhere near as sensitive as the ones on dslr cameras.. This camera takes a micro-SD card, not your usual sd memory card. Unfortunately this means its more of a pain to find in stores and more expensive too (hint, hint- buy it online). It also means you can't just plug in your memory card into a computer/photo printer without the adapter (this usually comes with new micro-sd cards though).

I am not going to get into technical details as you can easily read this on this site. I purchased this came in 2008 and have been using it every week for the past 6 years. This is my "pocket" camera that I almost always drop it into my pocket when I leave home. It is not necessarily for making a lot of great photo shots, however it is great to catch those unusual photos in your day to day life. I like to review restaurants and critique and I always have this little camera handy. The quality of the photos have been improved greatly on the later models but this one is great for small photos that I post on the internet. I had one problem with the camera in six years. The memory card that I inserted had a small rough place on the bottom left and the card got stuck in the camera. I was about ready to toss it when I learned that I could remove the broken tip of the memory card by carefully using a wire and file. After about 15 minutes I was able to retrieve the broken tip of the card, insert a new card and the  camera is back to working full time. This is a very rugged little camera that is made of lightweight metal and not plastic like so many are today. Also there is a view finder. Try to find a similar model today with a viewfinder at a reasonable price. I just purchased s second one off of eBay that is  a different color. I also use that one too. This was a great buy for a really neat little camera. It is no substitute for my Nikons but is a companion for them.

I've owned about 4 digital cameras in my life and this Fujifilm Finepix Z33WP was my favorite. (Granted they were all cheaper cameras.)  I broke my Canon camera at the beach (with barely any moisture or sand) and I broke my Nikon camera in a mosh pit so I looked for a waterproof camera with a stable, non retracting lens. This Z33WP was perfect! It went in the ocean with me many times, in the swimming pool (I tested it to about 12ft depth), in the hot tub, the rain, the sprinkler, the snow, the river, the sink, even some waterfalls, EVERYWHERE I could use it underwater I did and it ALWAYS held up without leaking! I had this camera since Target started selling it in 2009 and it lasted me until yesterday (2014), about 5 years! I was hell on this camera, so I'd say its definitely durable! Sand never hurt it, dropping it on everything never hurt it (I never put it in a case & I lost the wrist strap so it fell a lot, not to mention EVERYTHING in my purse always breaks but this camera never did), I even lost it out of my pocket in the pouring rain once and found it about 6 hours later laying in swampy flooded grass in perfect working order! The battery always lasted me all day if I used it after a full overnight charge. It takes decent pictures, the only problems I had were in low light conditions with blurriness. I was surprised at the sound quality compared to any other digital camera I've had, it was weird how much better everything sounded. From my fiance's acoustic and electric guitar jams, to louder live performances like concerts and rave events, even underwater videos of my niece yelling "Marco Polo". This camera had good sound quality in every tone, volume, and setting/climate/environment. It was a lot better than I thought it would be. Sometimes the flash is too bright up close and in low light (without flash) it can be too dark and blurry but with decent light it is good quality. It has a decent zoom and takes good quality magnified shots. The only otherissues I ever had with it were that the battery cover piece on the camera wore and cracked over time, and I cracked the screen somehow (small 1/2 inch crack on edge of screen) but the camera still never retained water or had any difficulties. Picture perfect ;)  After 5 years I broke it beyond repair but I am assuming normal people aren't as hard on digital cameras as me :P. Overall, it was a sturdy camera that does what it says and does it pretty well. I think it was worth every penny paid. Good starter camera for responsible teens.

Easily summed up. This $6,000 Leica M9 is inferior in every respect to any other camera system costing $6,000. There's nothing more to say.

I'm obviously a bit late to the party here, but I needed to wait for the price of an M9 to begin to return to earth before making my purchase.  I'll talk about this camera from the perspective of someone coming from an M6, and hope to address some questions or concerns others may have when deciding to make the jump from a film to a digital Leica M.. The camera is very close in weight to the M6, and the build quality feels similar as well.  The main thing you will notice right away is that the M9 is thicker than the M6.  It is noticeable, and when handling the two cameras side by side I prefer the smaller M6, however in practice I have found that I don't really care about the added thickness when I am out shooting.. The M9 has a larger shutter speed dial similar to the TTL version of the M6.  I will admit that this does handle better than the smaller dial on the classic M6.  The frame line preview works as before, and the finder is mostly similar to the M6, with some slight changes to the frame lines and a slightly different light meter with a dot between the opposing arrows that indicate over or under exposure.  None of these changes are problematic, as far as I am concerned.. The only other significant difference you will notice is the way the shutter button responds to pressure.  The M6 has a two stage button; half press to meter, full press to fire.  The M9 is a three stage, and can be configured to operate in several different ways.  The standard setup is you activate the meter with the first stage, lock the exposure with the second stage, full press to fire.  This can be changed in several ways, primarily by engaging the "soft" release function which trips the shutter at the second stage.  You may find you prefer this setup if you do not use the aperture priority function, and therefore have no need to lock the exposure.  In addition to the soft function, there is a "discrete" mode in which the shutter does not re-cock until you remove your finger from the shutter button.  I have found that I like this mode very much, as it allows you to take the photo with minimal noise and then lower the camera before re-cocking the shutter, which makes a brief whirring sound.. A note about that whirring sound:  In my opinion, it is the only mechanical function of this camera that could use improvement.  Quite frankly the sound is annoying, and doesn't sound like a Leica should sound.  Perhaps that's a ridiculous thing to say, but I am pretty sure if you are coming from a film M you will feel the same way.  The smooth film advance has been replaced by a whirring noise.  It's not the end of the world.  I'll get over it.. As far as the electronics are concerned, they're spartan and good enough.  The LCD is lousy by today's standards.  ISO can be changed easily by pressing the ISO button and turning the command wheel.  You can check your battery life easily, and battery life is relatively good.  The menu system is simple to negotiate; there aren't a lot of extraneous setting to fiddle around with, thank goodness.  The blown highlight/shadow indicators in the image review are accurate and helpful.  Frankly, you will likely set this camera up the way you want it, and then ignore the menu system most of the time.  Most electronic interaction is then limited to changing ISO on occasion (if you don't use auto-ISO) and checking your battery.  DNG files are fairly slow to write to the card, taking maybe 5 seconds per image.  You may run into the buffer if you shoot very quickly; I rarely have this problem.  The electronics thankfully do not really interfere with the overall shooting experience.. Image quality is a double edged sword.  This sensor likes to have some light, but not too much.  Highlight recovery isn't as good as a modern day DSLR.  Watch out you don't blow your highlights too badly.  when they're gone, they're gone.  There can also be some strange artifacting around badlyblown areas.  (The center-weighted meter is very sensitive to highlights, I suspect for this reason.)  High ISO performance isn't wonderful either.  Frankly, I've mostly kept the M9 at ISO 800 or below, occasionally going to 1600.  This is good enough for me, but I admit I wouldn't complain if it were better!  Those used to shooting at 6400 on a current DSLR may find the performance lacking in this regard.  When used within its limitations, however, the M9 files are absolutely wonderful.  They record an amazing amount of detail; I have more or less refrained from adding any sharpening to the DNG files in post-processing.  They convert to black and white very well, which was of primary importance for me, making very nicely toned, rich black and white conversions.  I almost never work in color so I will refrain from commenting on the quality of the colors out of the M9.. If you are considering making the switch from an M6 or other film M, I think you will be happy with the M9.  You'll likely wish for an improvement in the sound of the shutter cocking, but otherwise you can pickup the M9 and basically shoot with it as you would a film M.  If you have not used a Leica and are wondering if a rangefinder is for you, I would strongly recommend picking up a used film M with a 35 or 50mm lens and living with it for six months or so to determine whether or not a rangefinder system is right for you.

I bought this camera off a whim in the Dubai airport and was certain I was getting ripped off.  However, I've had this camera now for over 3 years and use it almost weekly in harsh conditions and it still works great an was one of my best purchases ever.  I have tried many other shockproof/waterproof cameras before only to have them survive one trip then die.  I live in sub-Saharan Africa where it's constantly dusty.  This camera has been to the bottom of Lake Malawi, in the oceans in Mozambique, up Kilimanjaro, snows of Alaska and has yet to let me down.  I have dropped it many times from heights that would normally destroy a camera, but this one just bounces and continues working.  I've dropped it 100 m down in a lake, found it 3 hours later and still worked fine.  It's been in many a monsoon rainstorm, sandstorms, and snow storms.. I would suggest getting the camera with it's small plastic protection sheath (not the large one); this helps keep the dirt, sand, and water out of the internal portions.  The camera will tell you when there's a piece of sand in the insides (it's never been wrong).. Photo quality is great and I'm often asked if photos are off an SLR.  Zoom though compromises the quality and photos become grainy when blown up.. Underwater pictures are clear and does an excellent job capturing underwater color.. If want a camera that you can abuse and will be forgiving, go with this Lumix.

OK.  I'm giving this 3-stars ONLY because of the fact that this was NOT the product I had originally bought. Apparently, if they are out of the product you pay for, they simply send you the next step up instead. And it caused me to have to go buy an entirely different underwater housing so that I can take it diving in greater depths without worrying. This was addressed, and the seller refunded my difference, and actually the camera I bought is even better. So I'll chalk it up as a win-win.. That being said, these TS2 models are great! I've owned one before and took it around the world on dive trips a few times before it randomly died on dry land. The image quality isn't as stunning as my Canon Powershot G models, by any means, but they are rugged enough to take everywhere and not have to worry about rain or being on a boat, or sand. I just wish the color and clarity of images were a little better. But I know it's hard to compete with Canon, Fuji, or Sony in that field!. The model that I was actually sent when I purchased this product, was the Lumix TS-5 model. And, although this forced me to have to make another large purchase to have the underwater housing, I can honestly say the TS-5 model is actually quite a step up from the original one! There is an advanced underwater function that adds a bit of a red filter to get better color accuracy underwater, and there is also a handheld night shot setting, and a long exposure (15 or 30 seconds) that is great for taking low light images. I've noticed the lighting captures better as well. OH - and there's Wi-Fi on this one, so you can send images to your phone, in case you want to send someone images or post online while you're out of range of your computer. So there's that. Even though I was EXTREMELY unhappy when I made the purchase, this last dive trip has helped me warm up to the fact that I ended up getting a better camera.

I've owned about 4 digital cameras in my life and this Fujifilm Finepix Z33WP was my favorite. (Granted they were all cheaper cameras.)  I broke my Canon camera at the beach (with barely any moisture or sand) and I broke my Nikon camera in a mosh pit so I looked for a waterproof camera with a stable, non retracting lens. This Z33WP was perfect! It went in the ocean with me many times, in the swimming pool (I tested it to about 12ft depth), in the hot tub, the rain, the sprinkler, the snow, the river, the sink, even some waterfalls, EVERYWHERE I could use it underwater I did and it ALWAYS held up without leaking! I had this camera since Target started selling it in 2009 and it lasted me until yesterday (2014), about 5 years! I was hell on this camera, so I'd say its definitely durable! Sand never hurt it, dropping it on everything never hurt it (I never put it in a case & I lost the wrist strap so it fell a lot, not to mention EVERYTHING in my purse always breaks but this camera never did), I even lost it out of my pocket in the pouring rain once and found it about 6 hours later laying in swampy flooded grass in perfect working order! The battery always lasted me all day if I used it after a full overnight charge. It takes decent pictures, the only problems I had were in low light conditions with blurriness. I was surprised at the sound quality compared to any other digital camera I've had, it was weird how much better everything sounded. From my fiance's acoustic and electric guitar jams, to louder live performances like concerts and rave events, even underwater videos of my niece yelling "Marco Polo". This camera had good sound quality in every tone, volume, and setting/climate/environment. It was a lot better than I thought it would be. Sometimes the flash is too bright up close and in low light (without flash) it can be too dark and blurry but with decent light it is good quality. It has a decent zoom and takes good quality magnified shots. The only other issues I ever had with it were that the battery cover piece on the camera wore and cracked over time, and I cracked the screen somehow (small 1/2 inch crack on edge of screen) but the camera still never retained water or had any difficulties. Picture perfect ;)  After 5 years I broke it beyond repair but I am assuming normal people aren't as hard on digital cameras as me :P. Overall, it was a sturdy camera that does what it says and does it pretty well. I think it was worth every penny paid. Good starter camera for responsible teens.

I've now had my GE X5 for nearly 5 years and its still going strong. I absolutely love this thing and have even purchased a few more since to give as gifts.. One of the things I have noticed with this aging is when the camera sits and the batteries have begun to discharge is it will cause it to have a problem with the lens opening properly. Just don't try to push or pull it. This just indicates the batteries need changed, pretty simple solution. I use this a lot to take close up photos when I sell on eBay. Sometimes they are too good, if that seems wrong then I will try to explain.  These new digital cameras pick up more than what we would normally see with our plain vision or in other word every speck of dust or crazing in porcelain is enhanced making it show up and look much worse than what we really need to see.. Also sometimes when you are in good lighting and you take a photo of say a nice looking gal who seems to have perfect make-up.  well if she uses concealer around her eyes under the make up then that appears and looks like raccoon eyes. Its actually quite funny unless you are wanting that perfect family photo.. If you are expecting to take professional photos for something such as the main wedding pics then I would recommend something better however if you are going on vacation and just want an easy to use camera that takes good photos then at this price tit perfect.. One thing I did do was purchase larger cards for these but unless you take a whole lot of photos or plan to record a lot then I don't recommend too much space otherwise when you take it to get them printed you'll be there forever.. Bottom line, this is inexpensive, practical and a nice little camera to have.

I've been a fan of Canon since waaay back in the film days.  Canon quality was bar none; Canon even made copiers that were excellent.  So it was no wonder I bought this camera, after researching many models.  I bought  it because 1) it was heavy enough to hold in my hand (smaller cameras tend to "take wings and fly" while I'm shooting, thereby making a blurry picture), 2) it was a Canon, 3) it has a nice telephoto lens and 4) the screen on back  was large enough so that I didn't have to go running for my glasses every time I was shooting.  This was my first experience with a digital camera, if that gives you an idea.. What I now have with over two years of shooting is a serious problem with battery life.  At first, the alkalines (just two) seemed to last forever.  I didn't use video so it was no wonder. Then I decided to buy some rechargables when the alkalines started showing some wear.  A set of four RayoVac I thought should do the trick.  Well, for a while.  Then I thought it was the rechargables--could I have left them charging for too long?  Maybe.  The red light on the charger never went off after the first time I charged them and used them in the camera.  Hmmm.  Another set of rechargeables, 2800 mah, bought here on Amazon and specifically for the camera (at least it said).  And after the very first charge and battery insertion, the camera acted like I needed new ones after never having taken a shot.  So back to the alkalines.  Which seem to have it working, but with a limited number of shots.. With reading the reviews here, I seem to feel it's the camera and not the batteries.  How could this be?  But there seems to be a common thread with all the reviews--it's the camera.  And the sad thing is, I can't return it.  I just have to accept my camera is hooked on alkaline batteries, and some days it uses a lot of juice, and some days it doesn't.  Maybe it's time I bought the adapter and shelve the rechargables.

This is a great little point and shoot.  I have been looking for a second camera to use for photographing very realistic dolls I paint and sell.  I'd been using a Coolpix S4000, and had good results, but thought I'd try another Nikon with 20MP.  It was horrible- all photos were blurred, so I sent it back within 24 hours of getting it.. I came back to the S4000, and don't regret it at all.  I got a different color from my first, to tell them apart (personal photos vs. photos for selling the dolls).  There are many different settings for outdoors, portraits, macro, landscape, etc.  I keep both of them set on auto flash, and the doll camera is kept on Macro most of the time, for close ups on fingernails and eyes- when I crop them, they don't lose sharpness.  I've used the auto-timer with great success when I want to be in a photo (family shots).  I did a LOT of 35mm SLR photography in the past, and while I still enjoy those photographs, the photos from this is definitely adequate for my needs- whether family photos, outdoor photos, to take to museums, etc.. Bottom line:  It is a good enough camera to have gotten another one, 3 years after getting the first.

Then the camera would not turn on.  Come to find out water had gotten into the battery compartment and the batteries were rusted.  We tried cleaning the rust out and replacing the batteries, but the camera will still not turn on.  I called Kodak and they wanted to charge me $15.00 for the call.  I tried chat & email through Kodak and was told their support is not longer available for this DISCONTINUED product?!?!!?  I am furious, as we had the camera for less than a year.  It was still under warranty.  I am very disappointed in Kodak and do not plan to purchase any more items from them!

I received this camera as a gift. It worked fine for almost two years. But keep in mind I only used this camera on my summer kayak trips. About 4 times a summer the rest of the time it was unused and stored correctly. I took very good care of this camera. It was never abused or misused in anyway. I never dropped it even though it is supposed to be shock proof. I never left it submerged in water and never had it more then 2ft deep for short periods of time. That being said it was rarely used and looks brand new and basically is. But on my last trip it just quit working. After a day on the river I plugged it up to charge and it wouldn't charge, it wouldn't come on, it wouldn't do anything. And has never worked again. The olympus web site said a non warranty (over a year) repair would be $119.96. Though I was pleased with the quality of the pics this camera took it is not worth the cost of repair. My satisfaction with the rest of the camera functions on a scale of 1 to 10 I would have to say about a 5. I am going to purchase another waterproof camera but it will not be an olympus.

I have been using this camera for about 2 years now and found it a very problematic camera.  I use the zoom on the camera frequently and since the beginning and I have lost many a good photo because sometime when I push the zoom switch and the lens is extending to take the shot it will stop half way through and will give a message "Lens Error". I am then required to turn the camera off and back on and try to take the shot again. More often than not I will get the same "Lens Error" and the frustration is extreme. It also has a tendency to lock up where none of the buttons work, the lens won't move and the camera is completely frozen. At these times removing the battery is the only answer I've found.. When I was researching cameras to buy I thought.  "It's a Nikon, it has to be good", that turned out not to be the case. I sincerely wish I could say good things about this camera but my recommendation has to be to save yourself a lot of frustration and look elsewhere, don't spend your money on this problematic camera.

Ok.  I've had this for 3 years solid.  3 of us in my family use it almost daily so I can finally give an honest review.  You will almost certainly get blurry pictures no matter what you try.  The build and mechanics seem solid. and that's the only thing I can say positive.. If you are taking a picture of a STATIONARY object, with full daylight, outside, using a tripod, holding your breath, saying a prayer, and skipping the morning coffee so your hand doesn't have the slightest shake as you depress the button to take a picture. well shoot, then this camera is PERFECT for you.. However,. If you have children, pets, children in sports, fish, flowers that blow in the breeze, or family and friends that are still alive and breathing. well heck, this camera isn't for you.. Yes, you can play with all the settings all day long. sounds wonderful.  Not for me.  Good luck all.

So, I bought this camera to be a backup to my Nikon for a safari to Tanzania . Good thing I had it as carry on since my suitcase with the larger camera did not show up for 4 days.. The pictures it took were good, unless the object was moving. Once you click the shutter release it takes some time before the actual picture is taken but then the animal had moved and all you would see is the butt end of the animal.. Even under sports mode the same problem occurred. If the object was still, the pictures came out well. Also, under the super zoom mode the camera was very difficult to hold steady.. So here is my final recommendation. Great camera for basic daily use.. Not recommended for moving objects especially  if close by.. If you are going on a safari then get a real camera (Nikon, Canon etc) with at least a 400 or 500 mm zoom. At times my 300 zoom lens was inadequate.. Contact me for further Safari advice

Great camera with long range zooming capabilities. On one battery you should be able to get around 150-200 pictures, so you should probably carry a spare or two. Recently tested out the zoom range at the San Francisco Giants game.  I was sitting literally at the highest part of the upper deck well from the home plate, and still got a clear picture of the batter on the diamond back.  Although you get can only get 14mp at 10x, it's still capable of zooming up to 20x at 3mp.  You can also use it as a camcorder to record video's at 720p and still use the zoom capabilities. It will drain your battery pretty quick on camcorder though.  This is a very good point and shoot camera.

I had a planned trip for the Galapagos in May 2014 and already had a Panasonic Lumix waterproof camera.. However, when my traveling companion purchased this Fiji from Sam's Club, i went to the local gym to try both cameras out.. I thought the FinePix was superior to my Panasonic.  I ordered 2 Fiji FinePixs through amazon, one for my daughter in another state.  I did not have time to try mine out before my trip to Galapagos.. Alas, my Fiji had a lens that fogged, and yes, then thought photos are blurred.  The LCD stayed unreadable!  So I took pictures underwater "blind."  maybe a total of 5 of my photos were o.k.  (Only o.k. if lens not fogged.)  The camera instructions even said the lens could fog!!!  Fiji should recall this camera!. There were 16 guests on my boat in the Galapagos.  4, including me, had this Fiji camera.  Mine was the only one to function poorly, so that's only a 75% chance yours will work when you need it.. To my great surprise, my daughter's and my Fiji FinePix came from 2 different amazon suppliers.  And they did not come with a sanDisc, carrying case, etc.  The Fiji model from Sam's was cheaper, and had a "real" instruction book, and extras.. My friend took beautiful underwater pictures with her Fiji.  It is a shame that not all of these cameras work correctly.
